{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17620566","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17620566"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:44:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:44:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16635"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16635","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16635"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.62,0.03,0.07,0.17,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9326"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82768"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9326","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9326"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16635"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67878"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4939"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5202"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22099"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22902"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82768","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/82768"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man presents to an addiction clinic for opioid replacement therapy. He reports regular heroin use for the past three years. After his first dose of buprenorphine, he develops sweating, anxiety, and mild muscle aches despite having used heroin earlier that day.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best explains this clinical observation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Partial agonist activity with high receptor affinity","Pure antagonist activity at all receptors","Full agonist activity with low receptor affinity","Competitive inhibition of heroin metabolism","Direct stimulation of withdrawal centres"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBuprenorphine acts as a \u003Cstrong\u003Epartial agonist\u003C/strong\u003E at the \u003Cstrong\u003Emu-opioid receptor\u003C/strong\u003E with \u003Cstrong\u003Ehigh affinity\u003C/strong\u003E, meaning it strongly binds to opioid receptors and displaces full agonists like heroin. However, since it does not activate the receptor as fully as heroin, this can lead to \u003Cstrong\u003Eprecipitated withdrawal\u003C/strong\u003E if administered too soon after opioid use. Symptoms such as sweating, anxiety, and muscle aches occur because heroin is rapidly displaced, but buprenorphine provides only partial receptor activation, resulting in a net decrease in opioid effect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Ch3\u003EExplanation of Incorrect Options:\u003C/h3\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPure antagonist activity at all receptors\u003C/strong\u003E (e.g., naloxone) would cause a much more severe withdrawal than what is described.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFull agonist activity with low receptor affinity\u003C/strong\u003E would not displace heroin from receptors and would not trigger withdrawal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECompetitive inhibition of heroin metabolism\u003C/strong\u003E would prolong heroin\u2019s effects rather than cause withdrawal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect stimulation of withdrawal centres\u003C/strong\u003E is not a recognized physiological mechanism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBuprenorphine\u2019s pharmacological properties make it useful in opioid dependence treatment, as it reduces withdrawal severity while also blocking the effects of other opioids.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Buprenorphine is a partial agonist at mu opioid receptors and an antagonist at kappa opioid receptors.","Partial agonists have a ceiling effect on respiratory depression, making them safer than full agonists.","Buprenorphine\u0027s high affinity for opioid receptors allows it to displace and subsequently inhibit the effects of other opioids.","Precipitated withdrawal occurs when buprenorphine displaces full opioid agonists from receptors."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67878"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16635"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67878","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67878"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-30T23:56:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-30T23:58:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9326"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82768"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/t